  "prompt": "What is dyarchy and when was it introduced in India?",
  "response": "Dyarchy was a system of dual governance introduced in British India under the Government of India Act of 1919, also known as the Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms. This system was implemented in the provinces of British India and came into effect in 1921. Under dyarchy, the provincial subjects were divided into two categories: \"transferred\" and \"reserved.\"\n\n- **Transferred subjects** included areas such as education, health, agriculture, and local government. These were managed by Indian ministers who were responsible to the provincial legislative councils.\n  \n- **Reserved subjects** covered areas such as finance, police, and revenue. These remained under the control of the British-appointed governors and their executive councils, with no responsibility to the legislative councils.\n\nThe introduction of dyarchy was a step towards involving more Indians in governance, although it kept significant powers in the hands of the British authorities. This system continued until it was replaced by provincial autonomy under the Government of India Act of 1935.",
